<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06206161 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06206161 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  TAX; CHANGE; CONGRESS; LEGISLATION  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Government tax collectors and specialists who make a living advising taxpayersare offering the same message to Congress: simplify the tax system before itcollapses.;    &quot;The greatest challenge our tax system faces in the 1990s is toease the burden (of complexity) on taxpayers,&quot; Fred Goldberg, the InternalRevenue Service commissioner, said Tuesday. Once people conclude that it is&quot;too difficult, too time-consuming, too expensive to comply,&quot; many will stopcomplying, he said.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  WATCH OUT, THEY WANT TO SIMPLIFY YOUR TAXES  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Leonard Podolin of the American Institute of Certified Public Accountantstold the House Ways and Means Committee of recent estimates that costs toindividuals and businesses of complying with the tax law total as much as $120billion a year.;    &quot;The majority of individual taxpayers, especially thosewith simple financial affairs, should not have to seek professional help forpreparation of their returns,&quot; Podolin said. He noted IRS statistics thatnearly half of individual returns are prepared by professionals.;   Undermining the system;    &quot;Complexity . . . has reached the point at whichmany tax practitioners and taxpayers believe that it is undermining our systemof voluntary compliance,&quot; Podolin said.;    Peter L. Faber, testifying for theAmerican Bar Association, blamed the large numbers of tax changes enacted inrecent years. &quot;Fifteen years ago . . . I testified before Congress urging thatthe tax laws be simplified. I pointed out that the Internal Revenue Codecontained a single sentence that was almost twice as long as the GettysburgAddress,&quot; he said.;    &quot;That sentence is still there,&quot; Faber said. &quot;Ifanything, we have moved backward on the simplification front.&quot;;   Simplification bill;    The Ways and Means Committee is considering abipartisan simplification bill that would:;    (check) Allow a person to defertaxation on profits from the sale of an unlimited number of principal homesduring a two-year period. Present law allows this &quot;non-recognition&quot; of gainonly once unless a job-related move is involved.;    (check) Delay from June15 to July 15 the due date of the second quarterly estimated tax payment eachyear. These payments are made when taxpayers have significant amounts ofincome that are not subject to withholding. The administration opposes thischange.;    (check) Exempt from withholding only $500 a month of the pay of amilitary officer in a combat zone. That is the same amount that is exempt fromtax. Present law exempts all such pay from withholding, leaving some officersliable for large payments when they file their tax returns.;    (check) Removethe 10 percent luxury tax from accessories added to a high-price vehicle tomake it usable by a disabled person. The tax applies to that part of the priceof a vehicle -- including accessories added within six months -- above$30,000.;    (check) Simplify a household employer's payment and reporting ofSocial Security and income taxes withheld from the wages of domestics. Presentlaw generally requires four quarterly and one annual filing. The bill wouldeliminate those filings in favor of one annual report on the employer's taxreturn.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Washington  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910724  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  8A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  499  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday July 24, 199100206161,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE><